The paper deals with computing spectral functions of large matrices in a streaming setting with limited space, which involves techniques from data structures, information theory, linear algebra, numerical analysis, and signal processing. Therefore, the most likely category is cs.DS (Data Structures and Algorithms), which covers the design, analysis, and implementation of efficient algorithms and data structures for solving computational problems. The paper also involves compressive sensing and matrix factorization techniques, which are relevant to cs.IT (Information Theory) and cs.LG (Machine Learning), respectively. Moreover, the paper discusses numerical methods for computing matrix norms, which are relevant to cs.NA (Numerical Analysis) and cs.SI (Signal Processing).
